The paper discusses a security attack on hard disk drives (HDDs), which falls under the category of computer security (cs.CR). The attack exploits a physical phenomenon, which involves the mechanical and acoustic properties of the HDDs, making it relevant to the sub-category of distributed, parallel, and cluster computing (cs.DC). The paper also discusses the impact of the attack on the performance of real-world systems, which involves the analysis of data and information theory (cs.IT). Additionally, the paper discusses the feasibility of the attack in personal computers and CCTV systems, which involves the study of software engineering (cs.SE) and human-computer interaction (cs.HC), respectively.
